snippet.textDisplay: I've always been a fan of the arts but also a man of science and at times I tend to be cold and dismiss things i don't think are worthwhile as stupid or pointless. I did this for a second as he started his performance but began to look in wonder as he continued the act, and even laughed when the balloon began to pull him away. I'm not sure why but a sense of childlike wonder emerged and I thank you for this piece of art. It was almost looking at a moving painting, every posture and movement meant to convey a feeling, and I even felt a little sad as the balloon was granted its last and only wish, freedom.

snippet.textDisplay:
11:06 -13:30 If you imagine a balloon that is labeled as "problems" it makes it much more touching. As you see the performance his "problems" try to set him back, by pulling him the other direction, the actor decides to shake off his "problems" and pretend it didn't happen. As it happens again he confronts the "problem" demanding it to stop, but you know that doesn't happen in real life unless you take action. When the performer decided enough was enough and pulled out the needle to end his "problems", he realized that wasn't going to solve anything, so he just lets his "problems" roam free. After he came at a realization where he couldn't stop thinking about his "problems", he turns back to catch up to the balloon. Walking side by side with his "problems" or phrased differently, he faces the "problems" head on instead of just leaving it or trying to get rid of it by meaningless ways.

Just wanted to write this because I'm actually dealing with a few problems myself and tried to runaway or forget them, but I was done doing that. Not anything major though. It also fits the theme of life death kinda eh.
